{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RiwWHxs69q379Vvqcis8cr","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Concepts\n     6→\n     7→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n     8→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n     9→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    10→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    11→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    12→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n    13→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    14→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    15→\n    16→## Step Types\n    17→\n    18→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    19→\n    20→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    21→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    22→container.\n    23→\n    24→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    25→any deterministic check.\n    26→\n    27→A step with both `prompt` and `run`, or neither, is a parse error.\n    28→\n    29→## DSL Syntax\n    30→\n    31→```\n    32→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    33→  step code {\n    34→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    35→    container {\n    36→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    37→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    38→    }\n    39→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    40→  }\n    41→\n    42→  step check {\n    43→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    44→    results = [pass, fail]\n    45→  }\n    46→\n    47→  step review {\n    48→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    49→    input = step.code.output\n    50→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    51→  }\n    52→\n    53→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step\n    54→  code:success -> check\n    55→  code:fail -> abort\n    56→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    57→\n    58→  check:pass -> review\n    59→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    60→\n    61→  review:approved -> done\n    62→  review:changes_requested -> code\n    63→}\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→## Key Properties\n    67→\n    68→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    69→field makes it a script step.\n    70→\n    71→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    72→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    73→\n    74→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    75→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    76→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n    77→\n    78→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    79→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n    80→\n    81→## Execution Model\n    82→\n    83→The workflow graph is parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside the container.\n    84→The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the wiring to\n    85→the next step. This continues until a terminal step (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n    86→\n    87→All steps in a workflow run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally\n    88→across steps.\n    89→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01AkfWUPgq78MP7yViLUjjcD","session_id":"abc5f750-0862-4f12-8214-59a5ee9bdc43","uuid":"e64a1fd8-a5cf-4fa6-9517-555c68fc6eaa"}
